    ```javascript
function findSubarrayLength(nums, threshold) {
    let n = nums.length, left = 0, right = 0, sum = 0, maxLength = -1;

    while (right < n) {
        sum += nums[right];
        while (sum * (right - left + 1) < threshold * (right - left + 1)) {
            sum -= nums[left];
            left++;
        }
        maxLength = Math.max(maxLength, right - left + 1);
        right++;
    }

    return maxLength;
}
```

    The algorithm is a sliding window approach. We initialize left and right pointers at the beginning of the array, and a sum variable. We also initialize maxLength to -1 to handle the case where there is no valid subarray.

In the loop, we move the right pointer, adding the element at that position to the sum. We then check if the sum times the length of the current window (right - left + 1) is less than the threshold times the length of the current window. If it is, we move the left pointer and subtract that value from the sum to maintain the sum of elements in the window.

At each step, we update maxLength to the maximum of the current maxLength and the length of the current window (right - left + 1). This way, we store the maximum length we've found so far.

After the loop, we return maxLength, which is the final answer.

